node.text:
The @nba. @carnegiehall. @nytmag. These are just a few of the household names Bobby C. Martin Jr. has worked with to create enduring branding and visual identity systems. “Redesigning an American institution is absolutely terrifying,” said Bobby, co-founder of the New York branding and design agency @championsdesign. “But it’s also thrilling.”

We spent a day with Bobby, a member of our #BlackDesignVisionaries grant committee, at his East Village studio. Watch to hear about his visionary approach to graphic design. #ShareBlackStories

🎥 : @qledbetter 
Assistant camera: @yukiday
Sound: @philshipmansound

"Good design is design that listens to its audience," Asad said. "In any format — fashion, jewelry and accessories, buildings — a good design is one that listens to the needs of its audience and finds a solution for a specific problem."

#DesignItForThePlanet “Everyone is so confused by what food design is,” said @linyeezy (LinYee Yuan), the founder and editor-in-chief of @thisismold. “Is it plating? The shape of a pastry? It’s all of these things,” she said. But, she continued, “I was interested in how the professional practice of design could be leveraged to address the coming food crisis.” With 5 print issues to date and a final underway, MOLD Magazine has focused on 6 different themes, including: “Designing for the Human Microbiome,” “Waste” and “Designing for the Senses.” Each issue is a progressive conversation, in which Linyee brings together interdisciplinary voices, including food journalists, chefs, farmers, philosophers, designers, scientists, and artists.

When people think about the future of food, they’re thinking about food in a pill form, vaporized food —retrained and austere,” LinYee said. “That’s not a future any of us will participate in. If it’s going to be anything that moves us forward, it has to be full of joy.” 🍽✨

#FoodDesign #FutureofFood #SustainableEating

“I was the only Black kid in school,” said the Mexico City-based designer @MarkGrattan, who grew up in Ohio. “When you are different from everyone, you find ways to express your individuality. Creativity was my vehicle.” Mark credits his parents’ influence: His dad had a passion for woodworking and painting, and his mom, a teacher, encouraged her students to pursue their dreams. 

Mark, who studied at @PrattInstitute, launched @VIDIVIXIStudio in 2014 and later moved to Mexico City. “Once I left New York, I started designing for myself,” he said. Now, as he continues to expand his practice — which includes consulting for @saintheron — he’s refining his mission. “Originally, I just wanted to make pretty things,” he said. “Now I have a new purpose: to expose and diversify this industry.” And in the process, he said, he’s still learning. “I would prefer to fail than succeed, because that means there’s room for growth.”

#ShelfieSunday 📚 “This was a big achievement,” @ZViolette (Zachary Violette) said of the custom shelving system from @ModernShelving seen here — designed by his partner @SeanLitchfield, who also took this photo. It was the couple’s first real space “for study and contemplation” in New York City, where space is notoriously limited. Zachary was amazed that they could fit all of their books here, arranging them in such a way that the library feels “almost infinite” in the space. Although the two have since moved to a larger place, they “haven’t been able to produce anything as magical,” he said. “Something about a small space can produce a jewel box like this.” 💠

#OutsideIn 🪴For @0llah_la (Olga Kelniarz), this corner provides a respite, “far away from obligations and stress.” The design process behind this space wasn’t meticulously thought-out or even intentional; Olga simply tried to surround herself with things that underscored the feeling of being safe and at home. 🏡

Naturally, plants came into the picture. She started small, with just 3 plants she and her boyfriend united when they moved in together. But over the past year, caring for and learning about plants turned into a hobby and distraction. Now, Olga’s collection has grown into a lush indoor garden featuring Calatheas, a banana plant and a money tree. 🌱

node.text: #DesignInMotion 🔵 “Pleasure for the senses.” That’s how @lioncolony (Dave Oh) describes his ASMR videos, which incorporate soothing sounds and colorful visuals to create something infinite and therapeutic. For this playful animation, Dave used a post-modern palette and a series of abstract circles — with a dash of sugar. 🧸 And the sounds? They come from constant experimentation. Dave’s pro tip: “Mix similar-sounding effects to create your own sounds — for example, the sound of an egg cracking can be derived from a plastic bottle!” 🎧

#TheWorldNeedsMoreSpiralStaircases 🌀“Pause for a moment and discover the charms of architecture,” said @der_photomann (Thomas Reichart). Thomas, who has been photographing architecture for 2 decades, was drawn to this candy-colored stairwell for its pastel hues, narrow banisters and feeling of softness. Thomas found this hypnotizing view during a visit to Leipzig, Germany — a “fascinating old town” that, he said, invites you to explore. 🍬
